d) - all 3 allowed\n\nSo with strict round-robin and 1 RPS, all 10 requests would be allowed. This confirms the problem.\n\nFor effective throttling, I need a lower effective rate. One approach is to set limit-rps=1 but configure a smaller zone size and burst size = 0 in the ConfigMap, so the actual nginx rate limit per source IP in each replica is 1r/s. But the key issue is distribution across replicas.\n\nLet me consider a creative solution: using limit-connections=1 to limit to 1 concurrent connection per IP. Since the curl loop is sequential, this shouldn't cause throttling unless the connection lingers. Alternatively, I could modify the nginx ConfigMap to add custom configuration that creates a global shared memory zone, though that's per nginx instance. Or I could use annotations with a very low limit and set limit-burst-multiplier to 0, making the rate enforcement so strict that even 1 request per replica per second is enforced.\n\nActually, I'm realizing I might be overcomplicating this. In Kubernetes, the Service kube-proxy typically uses iptables DNAT with random selection rather than strict round-robin, so requests from the same source to the same destination service are randomly distributed across backends. This means occasionally 2 requests might hit the same replica within a second.\n\nWith 3 replicas and random selection, the probability that consecutive requests hit the same replica is about 1/3. With 10 requests and 0.5s sleep between them, I'd expect roughly 3 out of 9 consecutive pairs to hit the same replica, and since they're within the 1-second window, all 3 would get throttled. So I'd see some throttling, though it wouldn't be exactly \"1 RPS\" and it's stochastic and unpredictable. For a reliable test, I need deterministic throttling instead.\n\nThe real solution for multi-replica rate limiting is probably to use ingress-nginx's global rate limit feature with memcached, or configure the nginx ingress ConfigMap for shared rate limiting. But th