{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01XjUpFyHnJeuhq6CeqWAsS9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. So the ConfigMap already has:\n1. `allow-snippet-annotations: \"true\"` - This means I can use `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/server-snippet` or `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/configuration-snippet` annotations\n2. `http-snippet: limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=api_zone:10m rate=20r/m;` - There's already a zone defined: `api_zone` with rate 20r/m (20 requests per minute = ~0.33 RPS)\n3. `limit-req-status-code: \"429\"` - Returns 429 for throttled requests\n\nThe `api_zone` is set to 20r/m, which is about one request every three seconds. With three replicas each enforcing this limit independently, the aggregate across all replicas would be around 60r/m or 1 RPS total.\n\nIf I apply `limit_req zone=api_zone` without burst via a snippet annotation, the behavior depends on how requests distribute across replicas. At 2 RPS input with three replicas, each one receives roughly 0.67 RPS, which means every other request hitting the same replica gets throttled since the zone only permits one request per three seconds. The key insight is that the rate limit applies per nginx worker within each instance, not globally.\n\nSo with 10 test requests, I'd expect around 5 to be throttled (roughly 50%), while the `/health` ingress remains unaffected since it has no rate-limiting snippet. The implementation is straightforward: add a `configuration-snippet` to the `rate-api` ingress that applies the zone, and the existing ConfigMap already defines `api_zone` with the 20r/m setting. I see that setting the rate to 20 requests per minute per replica works out perfectly—across 3 replicas that's 60 requests per minute total, which equals 1 RPS. When the test sends 2 RPS, each replica only sees about 0.67 RPS, so roughly half the requests get throttled since the zone only allows 1 request every 3 seconds. This multi-replica approach is elegant because the per-instance rate limit naturally scales with the number of replicas to achieve the desired aggregate throughput.\n\nNow I need to add a `configuration-snippet` annotation to the `rate-api` ingress that applies the rate limiting directive, then verify that the `/api` endpoint gets throttled while `/health` remains unaffected. The standard annotation approach won't work here since it applies per-replica limits, giving us 3 RPS total across replicas. Instead, I'll add a configuration snippet to the ingress that references the pre-existing `api_zone` from the ConfigMap, which enforces the aggregate 20r/m limit across all replicas.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5397,"cache_read_input_tokens":32006,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":5397},"output_tokens":38,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7528de2a-04ad-4ee1-8791-50b7cb9b61fc","uuid":"f6e11de8-96d0-4c62-afba-448d588e4ddd","request_id":"req_011CcQ1DykFfPSpafLKCSdxf"}
