{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_016UjBARZ5Gv3HQBTuqPvV22","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The admission webhook is blocking the `configuration-snippet` because of security concerns. The admission webhook doesn't allow \"risky\" configuration snippets even with `allow-snippet-annotations: \"true\"` set. This is probably because of the newer ingress-nginx versions that have an annotation validator.\n\nLet me check what version of ingress-nginx is running and what options are available.\n\nThe admission webhook is strict about which annotations are allowed. I need to either:\n1. Use a different approach that doesn't require snippets\n2. Check if there's a way to bypass the annotation validation\n3. Try using standard annotations like `limit-rps` instead, which might not trigger the validation\n\nThe error about \"risky annotation based on ingress configuration\" suggests there's an `enable-annotation-validation` setting that's stricter than just `allow-snippet-annotations`. I could try disabling that in the ConfigMap, or I could work with the standard `limit-rps` annotation which should be allowed without triggering the security checks. I'm looking at the safe ingress-nginx annotations available, and `limit-rpm` stands out as an option I haven't fully explored yet. Setting it to 20 requests per minute would give roughly 1/3 req/s per replica, which across 3 replicas totals 1 RPS—well below the 2 RPS the test sends, so throttling should kick in reliably. The key difference is that `limit-rpm` creates its own zone rather than using the `api_zone` I defined earlier, but that shouldn't matter for the rate limiting to work.\n\nWith `limit-rpm: \"20\"` applied, each replica would allow about 0.33 RPS per source IP, so when 2 RPS comes in and distributes across the 3 replicas, each gets roughly 0.67 RPS—exceeding the limit and causing around 50% of requests to be throttled, which should clearly demonstrate the rate limiting in action.\n\nNow I'm considering the burst multiplier settings to control how aggressively excess requests are rejected. The standard rate-limiting annotations like `limit-rpm` should be allowed since they're in a different annotation group than the blocked ConfigurationSnippet. I'm thinking through using `limit-rpm: \"20\"` which translates to about 0.33 RPS per replica per IP, and since the test client sends 2 RPS from a single IP across 3 replicas, that should trigger throttling at roughly 0.67 RPS per replica.\n\nI'm also considering `limit-rps: \"1\"` with a controlled burst multiplier instead—setting `limit-burst-multiplier: \"1\"` would give a minimum burst of 1 request, allowing the first couple requests per second before throttling kicks in.\n\nActually, I'm overthinking this. Let me just apply the annotation with `limit-rpm: \"20\"` and `limit-burst-multiplier: \"1\"` to keep the burst minimal, then run the test to see how it behaves with the 10 requests.\n\nThe real issue is that the admission webhook is rejecting the `configuration-snippet` annotation. I need to either disable annotation validation entirely by setting `enable-annotation-validation: false` in the controller Deployment, or find the `allow-snippet-annotations` setting to enable snippets specifically.\n\nActually, looking at this more carefully, I could sidestep the webhook validation altogether by using the standard rate-limiting annotations like `limit-rps` and `limit-rpm` instead of relying on snippets.\n\nBut first, I should verify what version of ingress-nginx is running and check what controller arguments are currently configured.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2082,"cache_read_input_tokens":37403,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2082},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"