{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01BAXn86BZoQMcMrFcwr7AWK","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `--allow-snippet-annotations` flag is not recognized by this version of ingress-nginx (v1.14.1). So it's a ConfigMap-only setting, not a CLI flag. I need to revert the Deployment patch.\n\nSo the ConfigMap already has `allow-snippet-annotations: \"true\"`, but the webhook is still rejecting snippets. Why?\n\nLet me look at this from the source code perspective. In ingress-nginx v1.14, the `allow-snippet-annotations` setting should be read from the ConfigMap by the controller. But the webhook is running inside the same process. If the webhook reads the config from memory (which was loaded from ConfigMap at startup), it should see the `true` value.\n \nCould the controller have started before the ConfigMap was created? Looking at the timestamps, the original controller pod started around 12:44, but the ConfigMap was created at 12:45:10, so the controller was already running when the ConfigMap appeared.\n\nThis means the controller initially started without the ConfigMap and defaulted to `allow-snippet-annotations=false`. When the ConfigMap was later applied, the nginx configuration should have reloaded dynamically, but it seems like the webhook might not have picked up this change—possibly a bug where the webhook's in-memory configuration didn't refresh even though the ConfigMap was updated.\n\nI need to revert that bad Deployment patch first since the flag doesn't actually exist. Then I have a few paths forward: I could trigger a rolling restart of the controller pods so they start up with the ConfigMap already present and read the `allow-snippet-annotations: \"true\"` setting at initialization, or I could explore whether there's a way to achieve the rate limiting using only standard annotations instead of snippets.\n\nThe key question is whether the webhook caches the configuration at startup or if it dynamically watches for ConfigMap changes. If it's cached at startup, then restarting the pods after the ConfigMap is in place should work.\n\nGiven that the webhook is still blocking snippets even though the ConfigMap shows `allow-snippet-annotations: \"true\"`, a rolling restart seems worth trying. As for standard annotations, I'm realizing the core limitation: they create per-instance rate limits, so with 3 replicas I'd end up with 3 RPS total instead of the 1 RPS I need across all instances. There's a sweet spot between those extremes—the `api_zone` at 20r/m hits that balance. So my approach is to revert the bad Deployment patch, restart the controller with the correct ConfigMap that has `allow-snippet-annotations: \"true\"`, and then add the `configuration-snippet` annotation to the rate-api ingress.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":576,"cache_read_input_tokens":53779,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":576},"output_tokens":33,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7528de2a-04ad-4ee1-8791-50b7cb9b61fc","uuid":"28c722f6-8e23-4e1f-b170-2588708eab3f","request_id":"req_011CcQ1i2YTfmpeeUcXnLS6m"}
